<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes_for_Week_5:_3.1_Fixed.2C_Variable.2C_and_Total_Costs">Notes for Week 5: 3.1 Fixed, Variable, and Total Costs</span></h2>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="Measures_of_Costs">Measures of Costs</span></h1>
<p><strong><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fixed_cost">Fixed Costs</a> (FC)</strong>:  costs that do not vary with the quantity of output produced. They are expended even if nothing is produced at all.</p>
<p><strong><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variable_costs">Variable Costs</a> (VC)</strong>: costs that vary with the quantity of output produced.</p>
<p><strong><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_cost">Total Cost</a> (TC)</strong> is the sum of fixed and variable costs $$TC = FC + VC$$</p>
<p>Using this concepts the table for the hypothetical example is updated as:</p>
<table border="1">
  <tr>
    <td># of Cooks</td>
    <td># of Sandwiches</td>
